\begin_layout Standard
We trained a set of reservoirs to learn a simulation which governed by the
 NLS equation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial\tau}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial\xi^{2}}+\left|\psi\right|^{2}\psi=0
\]

\end_inset

with the amplitude envelope 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\xi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a function of propagation distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 and co-moving time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 A well known analytic solution of NLs is given by Akhmadiev breather given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(\xi,t)=\left[1+\frac{2(1-2a)\cosh\left(\lambda t\right)+i\lambda\sinh\left(\lambda t\right)}{\sqrt{2a}\cos\left(\Omega x\right)-\cosh\left(\lambda t\right)}\right]e^{it}
\]

\end_inset

the behaviour of the solution is governed by a single parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in(0,0.5)$
\end_inset

, another parameters are related with 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, namely the fundamental wave number 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=2\sqrt{1-2a}$
\end_inset

 and growth factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\sqrt{8a(1-2a)}$
\end_inset

.
 Based on this fundamental solution, higher order maximal intensity breather
 can be constructed by choosing particular 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2},a_{3}\ldots,a_{k}$
\end_inset

 such that under particular phase and amplitude ,the breathers collides
 at particular time and position resulting at a higher peak with the procedure
 given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chin2016a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We aimed at simulating the construction of 5
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 order breather on a uniform background describing a highly non-linear situation.
 The objective of this simulation is to investigate under what conditions
 the Reservoir Computing can learn and simulate the maximum peak amplitude
 of a breather in NLS.
 For that purpose, we intentionally hide the peak of thr breather from the
 training data and preserve it as a part of test set.
\end_layout

