\begin_layout Subsection
Performence Metric and General Result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To quantify the error between predictions, a metric should be defined.
 As we are interested in the prediction at maximum peak, we will only find
 the difference between prediction and the real solution at this particular
 point.
 Precisely, let the exact solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{10}(x)=\psi(x,t=10)$
\end_inset

 and prediction at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=10$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\psi}$
\end_inset

, we assume that both of them are elements in a normed space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X,\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert \right)$
\end_inset

 than the error is defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e=\frac{\left\Vert \hat{\psi}_{10}-\psi_{10}\right\Vert _{H^{1}}}{\left\Vert \psi_{10}\right\Vert _{H^{1}}}\label{eq:error}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

With 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}$
\end_inset

is the Sobolev space metric defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{H^{1}}=\left[\int_{X}\left|u\right|^{2}dx\right]^{\frac{1}{2}}+\left[\int_{X}\left|\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\right|^{2}dx\right]^{\frac{1}{2}}
\]

\end_inset

As our function is periodic, the spatial derivative is computed in the Fourier
 space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}=\mathcal{F}^{-1}\left\{ ik\mathcal{F}\left\{ u\right\} \right\} $
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

